.TH "TEMPORAL.ZONEDDATETIME.COMPARE" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.compare \- Temporal.ZonedDateTime.compare()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]Temporal.ZonedDateTime.compare()\f[B]\f[R] static method
returns a number (\-1, 0, or 1) indicating whether the first date\-time
comes before, is the same as, or comes after the second date\-time.
It is equivalent to comparing the \f[CR]epochNanoseconds\f[R] of the two
date\-times.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.compare(dateTime1, dateTime2)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]dateTime1\f[R]
A string, an object, or a \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instance
representing the first date\-time to compare.
It is converted to a \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object using the
same algorithm as \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from()\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]dateTime2\f[R]
The second date\-time to compare, converted to a
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object using the same algorithm as
\f[CR]dateTime1\f[R].
.SS Return value
Returns \f[CR]\-1\f[R] if \f[CR]dateTime1\f[R] comes before
\f[CR]dateTime2\f[R], \f[CR]0\f[R] if they are the same, and
\f[CR]1\f[R] if \f[CR]dateTime1\f[R] comes after \f[CR]dateTime2\f[R].
They are compared by their underlying instant values, ignoring their
calendars or time zones.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using Temporal.ZonedDateTime.compare()
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] dt1 = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(\(dq2021\-08\-01T01:00:00[Europe/London]\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] dt2 = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(\(dq2021\-08\-02T00:00:00[Europe/London]\(dq);
console.log(Temporal.ZonedDateTime.compare(dt1, dt2)); \f[I]// \-1\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] dt3 = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(\(dq2021\-08\-01T00:00:00[Europe/London]\(dq);
console.log(Temporal.ZonedDateTime.compare(dt1, dt3)); \f[I]// 1\f[R]
.EE
.SS Sorting an array of date\-times
The purpose of this \f[CR]compare()\f[R] function is to act as a
comparator to be passed to \f[CR]Array.prototype.sort()\f[R] and related
functions.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] dateTimes = [
  Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(\(dq2021\-08\-01T00:00:00[America/New_York]\(dq),
  Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(\(dq2021\-08\-01T00:00:00[Asia/Hong_Kong]\(dq),
  Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(\(dq2021\-08\-01T00:00:00[Europe/London]\(dq),
];

dateTimes.sort(Temporal.ZonedDateTime.compare);
console.log(dateTimes.map((d) \f[B]=>\f[R] d.toString()));
\f[I]// [ \(dq2021\-08\-01T00:00:00+08:00[Asia/Hong_Kong]\(dq, \(dq2021\-08\-01T00:00:00+01:00[Europe/London]\(dq, \(dq2021\-08\-01T00:00:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq ]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
Note that they are compared by their instant values.
In the very rare case where you want to compare them by their
wall\-clock times, convert them to \f[CR]PlainDateTime\f[R] first.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] dateTimes = [
  Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(\(dq2021\-08\-01T00:00:00[America/New_York]\(dq),
  Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(\(dq2021\-08\-01T00:00:00[Asia/Hong_Kong]\(dq),
  Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(\(dq2021\-08\-01T00:00:00[Europe/London]\(dq),
];

dateTimes.sort((a, b) \f[B]=>\f[R]
  Temporal.PlainDateTime.compare(a.toPlainDateTime(), b.toPlainDateTime()),
);
console.log(dateTimes.map((d) \f[B]=>\f[R] d.toString()));
\f[I]// [ \(dq2021\-08\-01T00:00:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq, \(dq2021\-08\-01T00:00:00+08:00[Asia/Hong_Kong]\(dq, \(dq2021\-08\-01T00:00:00+01:00[Europe/London]\(dq ]\f[R]
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime.prototype.equals()\f[R]
